UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 AN ACT relating to gubernatorial transitions.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 Section 1. KRS 15.020 is amended to read as follows:
4 (1) The Attorney General is the chief law officer of the Commonwealth of Kentucky
5 and all of its departments, commissions, agencies, and political subdivisions, and
6 the legal adviser of all state officers, departments, commissions, and agencies, and
7 when requested in writing shall furnish to them his or her written opinion touching
8 any of their official duties, and shall prepare proper drafts of all instruments of
9 writing required for public use, and shall exercise all common law duties and
10 authority pertaining to the office of the Attorney General under the common law,
11 except when modified by statutory enactment.
12 (2) The Attorney General shall communicate with the Legislative Research
13 Commission as required by KRS 418.075.
14 (3) (a) Except as otherwise provided in KRS 48.005 and 2000 Ky. Acts ch. 483,
15 sec. 8, the Attorney General shall appear for the Commonwealth in all cases
16 in the Supreme Court or Court of Appeals wherein the Commonwealth is
17 interested, and shall also commence all actions or enter an appearance in all
18 cases, hearings, and proceedings in and before all other courts, tribunals, or
19 commissions in or out of the state, and attend to all litigation and legal
20 business in or out of the state required of the office by law, or in which the
21 Commonwealth has an interest, and any litigation or legal business that any
22 state officer, department, commission, or agency may have in connection
23 with, or growing out of, his, her, or its official duties, except where it is made
24 the duty of the Commonwealth's attorney or county attorney to represent the
25 Commonwealth. When any attorney is employed for any said agency, the
26 same shall have the approval of such agency before such employment.
27 (b) 1. As used in this paragraph, "entity of the executive branch" means:
Page 1 of 14
XXXX 1/15/2026 7:31 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 a. Any department, program cabinet, or administrative body
2 enumerated in KRS 12.020;
3 b. Any department, office, administrative body, or executive branch
4 agency attached to an executive branch department or program
5 cabinet enumerated in KRS 12.020; or
6 c. Any officer of any department, office, program cabinet,
7 administrative body, or executive branch agency listed in
8 subdivision a. or b. of this subparagraph.
9 2. a. Within one hundred eighty (180) days before a gubernatorial
10 inauguration, the Attorney General shall, in consultation with
11 the secretary of the Finance and Administration Cabinet, review
12 and approve or disapprove any settlement of pending or
13 threatened litigation involving an entity of the executive branch
14 in which the settlement amount exceeds one million dollars
15 ($1,000,000).
16 b. A settlement shall not be entered into or approved by an entity of
17 the executive branch without prior approval of the Attorney
18 General as provided in subdivision a. of this subparagraph.
19 3. The requirements of this paragraph shall apply to any program
20 cabinet, department, administrative body, or agency created by or
21 attached to an entity of the executive branch after the effective date of
22 this Act.
23 (4) Notwithstanding any other statute or provision to the contrary, the Attorney General
24 may bring any action challenging the constitutionality of a Kentucky statute,
25 executive order, administrative regulation, or order of any cabinet, program cabinet,
26 or department under KRS Chapter 12. The action may be brought in any county
27 where the alleged constitutional harm has occurred or could be reasonably
Page 2 of 14
XXXX 1/15/2026 7:31 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 presumed to occur.
2 (5) If any funds of any kind or nature whatsoever are recovered by or on behalf of the
3 Commonwealth, in any action, including an ex rel. action where the Attorney
4 General has entered an appearance or is a party according to statutory or common
5 law authority, those funds shall be handled under KRS 48.005.
6 Section 2. KRS 18A.111 is amended to read as follows:
7 (1) Except when appointed to a job classification with an initial probationary period in
8 excess of six (6) months, and except as provided in KRS 18A.005 and this section,
9 an employee shall serve a six (6) months probationary period when he or she is
10 initially appointed to the classified service. An employee may be separated from his
11 or her position, reduced in class or rank, or replaced on the eligible list during this
12 initial probationary period and shall not have a right to appeal, except as provided
13 by KRS 18A.095. The employee may be placed on an eligible list but shall not be
14 certified to the agency from which he or she was separated unless that agency so
15 requests. Unless the appointing authority notifies the employee prior to the end of
16 the initial probationary period that he or she is separated, the employee shall be
17 deemed to have served satisfactorily and shall acquire status in the classified
18 service.
19 (2) An employee who satisfactorily completes the initial probationary period for the
20 position to which he or she was initially appointed to the classified service shall be
21 granted status and may not be demoted, disciplined, dismissed, or otherwise
22 penalized, except as provided by the provisions of this chapter.
23 (3) An employee ordered reinstated by the board shall not be required to serve a
24 probationary period unless the board rules otherwise.
25 (4) An employee with status, who has been promoted, shall serve a promotional
26 probationary period of six (6) months, except for those employees granted leave in
27 excess of twenty (20) consecutive work days during this period. Such probationary
Page 3 of 14
XXXX 1/15/2026 7:31 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 periods shall be extended as prescribed in KRS 18A.005. During this period, he or
2 she shall retain the rights and privileges granted by the provisions of this chapter to
3 status employees.
4 (5) An employee with status may request that he or she be reverted to a position in his
5 or her former class at any time during the promotional probationary period.
6 (6) A laid-off employee who accepts a bona fide written offer of appointment to a
7 position shall not be required to serve an initial probationary period. He or she shall
8 be an employee with status and shall have all rights and privileges granted
9 employees with status under the provisions of this chapter.
10 (7) At any time in the eighteen (18) months prior to a gubernatorial inauguration, a
11 person who is appointed to a position in the classified service and who previously
12 held a position that was unclassified under subsection (1) of Section 3 of this Act
13 shall:
14 (a) Be required to serve an initial probationary period of twenty-four (24)
15 months regardless of whether he or she previously had status in the
16 classified service; and
17 (b) Not be entitled to any preference in hiring or reemployment,
18 notwithstanding KRS 18A.130 and 18A.135[A former unclassified employee
19 under KRS 18A.115(1)(d), (e), (f), (g), (h), or (i) shall serve an initial
20 probationary period of twelve (12) months if the employee is appointed to a
21 position in the classified service, unless that employee had previously had
22 status in the classified service or had been separated from his or her previous
23 unclassified position for at least one hundred eighty (180) days prior to the
24 effective date of his or her appointment to the classified service].
25 (8) Notification to an employee on initial or promotional probation of the reason the
26 probationary employment has been terminated by the appointing authority shall not
27 confer a right to appeal to the board.
