19 Section 4. KRS 45A.095 is amended to read as follows:
20 (1) As used in[For purposes of] this section:
21 (a) "Emergency condition" means a situation which creates a threat or impending
22 threat to public health, welfare, or safety such as may arise by reason of fires,
23 floods, tornadoes, other natural or man-caused disasters, epidemics, riots,
24 enemy attack, sabotage, explosion, power failure, energy shortages,
25 transportation emergencies, equipment failures, state or federal legislative
26 mandates, or similar events. The existence of the emergency condition creates
27 an immediate and serious need for services, construction, or items of tangible
Page 10 of 14
XXXX 1/15/2026 7:31 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 personal property that cannot be met through normal procurement methods
2 and the lack of which would seriously threaten the functioning of government,
3 the preservation or protection of property, or the health or safety of any
4 person;
5 (b) "Executive branch agency" means all executive branch departments,
6 offices, program cabinets and their respective departments, and
7 administrative bodies enumerated in KRS 12.020, and any other executive
8 branch agencies immediately attached to a department, office, program
9 cabinet, or administrative body enumerated in KRS 12.020; and
10 (c)[(b)] "Sole source" means a situation in which there is only one (1) known
11 capable supplier of a commodity or service, occasioned by the unique nature
12 of the requirement, the supplier, or market conditions.
13 (2) A contract may be made by noncompetitive negotiation only:
14 (a) For sole source purchases;
15 (b) When competition is not feasible, as determined by the purchasing officer in
16 writing prior to award, under administrative regulations promulgated by the
17 secretary of the Finance and Administration Cabinet or the governing boards
18 of universities operating under KRS Chapter 164A;
19 (c) When emergency conditions exist; or
20 (d) For sponsorships, naming rights, or other advertising or similar considerations
21 for which competition is not feasible.
22 (3) Insofar as it is practical, no fewer than three (3) suppliers shall be solicited to
23 submit written or oral quotations whenever it is determined that competitive sealed
24 bidding is not feasible. Award shall be made to the supplier offering the best value.
25 The names of the suppliers submitting quotations and the date and amount of each
26 quotation shall be placed in the procurement file and maintained as a public record.
27 (4) Competitive bids may not be required:
Page 11 of 14
XXXX 1/15/2026 7:31 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 (a) For contractual services where no competition exists, such as telephone
2 service, electrical energy, and other public utility services;
3 (b) Where rates are fixed by law or ordinance;
4 (c) For library books;
5 (d) For commercial items that are purchased for resale;
6 (e) For interests in real property;
7 (f) For visiting speakers, professors, expert witnesses, and performing artists;
8 (g) For personal service contracts executed pursuant to KRS 45A.690 to 45A.725;
9 (h) For agricultural products in accordance with KRS 45A.645; and
10 (i) For contracts entered into by the president of the Kentucky Horse Park for
11 emergency purchases pursuant to KRS 148.320(5).
12 (5) The chief procurement officer, the head of a using agency, or a person authorized in
13 writing as the designee of either officer may make or authorize others to make
14 emergency procurements when an emergency condition exists.
15 (6) The Finance and Administration Cabinet may negotiate directly for the purchase of
16 contractual services, supplies, materials, or equipment in bona fide emergencies
17 regardless of estimated costs. The existence of the emergency shall be fully
18 explained, in writing, by the head of the agency for which the purchase is to be
19 made. The explanation shall be approved by the secretary of the Finance and
20 Administration Cabinet and shall include the name of the vendor receiving the
21 contract along with any other price quotations and a written determination for
22 selection of the vendor receiving the contract. This information shall be filed with
23 the record of all such purchases and made available to the public. Where practical,
24 standard specifications shall be followed in making emergency purchases. In any
25 event, every effort should be made to effect a competitively established price for
26 purchases made by the state.
27 (7) Subsection (6) of this section shall not apply to emergency purchases made
Page 12 of 14
