UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 pursuant to KRS 148.320(5).
2 (8) In the one hundred eighty (180) days preceding a gubernatorial inauguration, an
3 executive branch agency may execute or renew a contract by noncompetitive
4 negotiation only when the secretary of the Finance and Administration Cabinet
5 and the State Treasurer both certify that the contract is necessary because of the
6 existence of an emergency condition.
7 Section 5. KRS 171.530 is amended to read as follows:
8 (1) Except as provided in subsection (2) of this section, the commission shall establish
9 standards for the selective retention of records of continuing value, and the
10 department shall assist state and local agencies in applying such standards to
11 records in their custody. The department shall notify the head of any such agency of
12 any actual, impending, or threatening unlawful removal, defacing, alteration, or
13 destruction of records in the custody of such agency that has come to its attention,
14 and initiate action through the agency head or Attorney General for the recovery of
15 such records as shall have been unlawfully removed and for such other redress as
16 may be provided by law.
17 (2) (a) For a period of twelve (12) months prior to the date of a gubernatorial
18 inauguration, all documents that are public records as defined in KRS
19 61.870 shall be preserved for the Governor-elect and his or her
20 gubernatorial transition team if the subject matter includes:
21 1. Contracts that have been granted, altered, or amended;
22 2. Appointments to boards and commissions;
23 3. Permits and licenses granted and revoked;
24 4. Pardons;
25 5. Pay raises, promotions, and grade level changes of executive branch
26 employees;
27 6. Litigation; or
Page 13 of 14
XXXX 1/15/2026 7:31 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1164
1 7. Any record relating to campaign donations of any kind.
2 (b) On the day after the Governor-elect is determined, the Governor shall make
3 available to the Governor-elect and his or her gubernatorial transition team
4 all public records pertaining to the subjects referenced in paragraph (a) of
5 this subsection.
6 Section 6. KRS 171.990 is amended to read as follows:
7 (1) Any person or library board violating any of the provisions of KRS 171.240 to
8 171.300 shall be fined not less than ten ($10) nor more than one hundred dollars
9 ($100) for each offense.
10 (2) The board for certification of librarians may revoke the certificate of any person
11 violating any of the provisions of KRS 171.240 to 171.300, or any of the
12 regulations as established by the board for certification.
13 (3) Any person knowingly violating the rules and regulations of the department
14 pursuant to the provisions of KRS 171.450, 171.560, 171.670, 171.710, or 171.720
15 or subsection (2) of Section 5 of this Act is guilty of a Class A misdemeanor and is
16 also liable for damages or losses incurred by the Commonwealth. Any state
17 employee who knowingly violates these provisions shall also be subject to
18 dismissal from state employment upon a determination of fact, at a hearing, that a
19 serious violation did occur. The employee's right to appeal to the state personnel
20 board shall not be[is not] abridged or denied. In the event of an appeal, the decision
21 of the state personnel board is final. The Attorney General shall have concurrent
22 original jurisdiction to enforce this subsection.
23 (4) State employees dismissed under the provision of subsection (3) of this section shall
24 have the right to reapply for state employment in accordance with state personnel
25 rules governing dismissal. Such individuals shall have the full rights and privileges
26 accorded under applicable equal opportunity laws.
